  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Altitude</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Quito is at 9,350 feet. Many people feel altitude effects for the first week or two. Take it easy initially, stay hydrated, and consider starting in Guayaquil or the coast if you're concerned.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming Fast Internet Everywhere</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While Cuenca and Quito have good internet in modern buildings, speeds vary. If internet is critical, verify before signing a lease—or choose an apartment with dedicated fiber.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Getting Evacuation Coverage</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you plan to visit the Galápagos, Amazon, or remote highlands, evacuation coverage is essential. Medical facilities in these areas are basic.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping the Cedula</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The cedula (Ecuadorian ID) is important for daily life. Get it within 30 days of arrival to avoid complications with banking, phone contracts, and other services.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Everything in English</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While Cuenca's expat community is large, Ecuador is a Spanish-speaking country. Basic Spanish will significantly improve your daily life. Take classes—they're cheap and available everywhere.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Ecuador -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Ecuador</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Ecuador has a two-tier healthcare system. Public healthcare (IESS) is available to residents, while private healthcare offers shorter waits and more amenities. Both are affordable by US standards.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Facilities</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Hospital Metropolitano</strong> - Quito, JCI-accredited, international standard</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital de los Valles</strong> - Quito, modern private hospital</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital Santa Inés</strong> - Cuenca, popular with expats</li>
      <li><strong>Clínica Kennedy</strong> - Guayaquil, largest private hospital network</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Public vs Private Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">IESS (Public)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Cost:</strong> Small monthly contribution</li>
          <li>• <strong>Access:</strong> After residency established</li>
          <li>• <strong>Quality:</strong> Variable, can be good</li>
          <li>• <strong>Wait times:</strong> Can be long</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Private</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Cost:</strong> Affordable (by US standards)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Access:</strong> Immediate, cash or insurance</li>
          <li>• <strong>Quality:</strong> Good to excellent</li>
          <li>• <strong>Wait times:</strong> Minimal</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Private, Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> $25-50</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> $40-80</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency room:</strong> $75-200</li>
      <li><strong>Dental cleaning:</strong> $25-40</li>
      <li><strong>MRI:</strong> $150-300</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is Ecuador dollarized?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Ecuador adopted the US dollar in 2000 after an economic crisis. This means all prices are in USD, ATMs dispense dollars, and there's no exchange rate risk. For remote workers earning in USD, this is a significant advantage.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is $1,350/month enough to live on in Ecuador?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, especially in cities like Cuenca. Budget-conscious expats live comfortably on $1,000-1,400/month. However, if you want a more comfortable lifestyle with regular dining out and travel, $1,800-2,200/month is more realistic.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How's the internet for remote work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Internet in Quito and Cuenca is generally adequate for remote work (25-100 Mbps in modern buildings). Fiber is available in newer constructions. Check internet before signing a lease if it's critical for your work.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I visit the Galápagos?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes! The Galápagos Islands are an Ecuadorian territory and easily accessible from Quito or Guayaquil (about 2-hour flight). Budget for $100/day minimum on the islands plus $100 park fee. It's worth every penny.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the path to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 21 months of continuous residence on a temporary visa, you can apply for permanent residency. After 3 years of permanent residency, you can apply for citizenship. Ecuador allows dual citizenship.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Cuenca or Quito—which is better?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Cuenca: Smaller, more manageable, perfect weather, large expat community, colonial charm, lower cost. Quito: Larger, more cosmopolitan, better nightlife, higher altitude, more flight options, faster internet. Most first-time expats start in Cuenca.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

